{
  "texts": [
    "Kolovos et al. [36] found that from a societal perspective the intervention was not cost-effective in comparison with the enhanced usual care.Twomey et al.",
    "[38] examined the effectiveness of a self-help CBT intervention (\"MoodGYM\") on reducing the general psychological distress, stress, depression, anxiety, and impaired daily functioning symptoms.",
    "Twomey et al. [38] found symptom improvement for the treated individuals with a within-group effect size of Cohen d =.4 for depression and Cohen d =.14 for anxiety.",
    "Nevertheless, similar to the studies conducted by Kenter et al. [11] and Kolovos et al., [36] they did not find significant differences between the intervention group and the simply waiting control group (depression: F 1, 64 = 2.99, P >.05; anxiety: F 1, 64 = 1.72, P >.05).",
    "[38] At post treatment, small between-group effect sizes were found for both depression and anxiety (see Table 5), suggesting that \"MoodGYM\" was not more effective than the control condition."
  ]
}